        <!-- Section 1: Introduction -->
        <article class="about-teacher-block about-teacher-block-1" data-scroll-item>
            <div class="about-teacher-text-wrapper">
                <div class="about-teacher-section">
                    <h2 class="about-teacher-heading">Why I Teach the Bansuri </h2>
                    <p>
                        What's true about us —
                        we became great reductionists.
                        peace reduced to meditation app algorithms
                        habits reduced to tracking apps & smart watches
                        desires reduced to aesthetics of outcomes
                        Everything keeps getting sharper — except human emotions and beliefs.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        But what is real?
                        I didn't have the answer until I discovered a field I'd cherish my whole life.
                        Even though I knew something was wrong,
                        I thought, <strong> "This is what I need to do to be all there." </strong>
                        Until my mid-20s, when I started experiencing the pressure of adulthood left, right and
                        center.
                        I put down the business books and started reading people who lived centuries ago.  of being with the breath—matters. It steadies you. It gives you back your own rhythm.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        And the answer I got is:
                        Indian classical music is the most practical field in the
                        world.
                        Not because it is ancient — but because it trains your attention, your nervous
                        system, and your way of being.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="about-teacher-image-wrapper">
                <img src="images/kuldeep5.jpeg"
                     alt="Kuldeep Mishra practicing in stillness"
                     class="about-teacher-image" />
            </div>
        </article>

        <!-- Section 2: Why Bansuri -->
        <article class="about-teacher-block about-teacher-block-2" data-scroll-item>
            <div class="about-teacher-image-wrapper about-teacher-image-group">
                <img src="images/guru.jpeg"
                     alt="The tradition of one-on-one learning"
                     class="about-teacher-image about-teacher-image-soft" />
                <img src="images/guru2.jpeg"
                     alt="Traditional flute teaching practice"
                     class="about-teacher-image about-teacher-image-soft" />
            </div>
            <div class="about-teacher-text-wrapper">
                <div class="about-teacher-section">
                    <h2 class="about-teacher-heading">Why Bansuri</h2>
                    <p>
                        But again within it arises one question:
                        <strong> Why bansuri? </strong>
                        Because this instrument doesn’t force you into anything.
                        It leaves you free to decide how you think and how you respond.
                        It made me feel capable again.
                        It introduced me to the real strength: <strong> self-mastery </strong>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        My journey in bansuri has been shaped deeply by my two gurus
                       <strong> Shiromani Pandit Himanshu Nanda </strong>, a world-class flautist and senior disciple of <strong> Pandit
                        Hariprasad Chaurasia </strong>. and <strong> Shri Akash Pattnaik </strong>,
                        whose guidance and patience grounded my practice and my way of teaching.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </article>

        <!-- Section 3: My Guru -->
        <article class="about-teacher-block about-teacher-block-3" data-scroll-item>
            <div class="about-teacher-text-wrapper">
                <div class="about-teacher-section">
                    <h2 class="about-teacher-heading"> The Worldview Behind My Approach </h2>
                    <p>
                        My focus is simple:
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                clear fundamentals
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                steady practice
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                calm before competence
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                zero pressure learning environment
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                        </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="about-teacher-image-wrapper">
                <img src="images/flute.jpeg"
                     alt="The bansuri in traditional learning"
                     class="about-teacher-image" />
            </div>
          
        </article>


        <!-- Section 5: My Future Plan -->
        <article class="about-teacher-block about-teacher-block-5" data-scroll-item>
            <div class="about-teacher-image-wrapper">
                <img src="images/kuldeep4.jpeg"
                     alt="Dedicated to traditional learning"
                     class="about-teacher-image" />
            </div>
            <div class="about-teacher-text-wrapper">
               
                <div class="about-teacher-section">
                    <h2 class="about-teacher-heading">What Students Experience & How We Work </h2>
                    <p>
                        Many students had tried on their own, quit, or believed they “weren’t talented enough.”
                        When they practiced this way — patiently, without pressure — they progressed further than
                        they expected and felt better, not just played better.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        To date, I’ve guided <strong> 250+ students worldwide</strong>, many of them complete beginners with no
                        musical background.
                    </p>
                   
                </div>
            </div>
          
        </article>

        <!-- Section 6: Closing Reflection -->
        <article class="about-teacher-closing" data-scroll-item>
            <div class="about-teacher-closing-content">
                <p>
                    I can’t accept everyone.
                    But if you value patience, traditional learning, and consistent practice, I’d be glad to talk with
                    you about beginning.
                </p>
                <div class="about-teacher-cta-wrapper">
                    <a href="https://calendar.app.google/iew7hQRcnT1rQyse7" class="cta cta-about" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
                        Begin with a First Session
                    </a>
                </div>
            </div>
        </article>

    </div>
